attributes.title: Viewing angle in novice L2 lexical learning in British Sign Language (BSL)

q1.value: Viewing angle in novice L2 lexical learning in British Sign Language (BSL)

q2.value: Freya Watkins, Bodo Winter, Robin Thompson

q3.value:
Insights from visual ‘noise’ during sign language processing may help us understand more about how signs are represented in the mental lexicon, and how comprehension is achieved despite variation in input. One type of visual noise is the viewing angle at which a comprehender is situated relative to somebody signing. Watkins et al. (in prep) showed BSL signers of various degrees of fluency were slower and less accurate to make semantic decisions to signs viewed at side angles (45°, 90°) vs. a front angle (0°). We also found that for L1 Deaf signers, mental rotation ability correlated strongly with performance in the BSL angle processing task, whereas for L2 intermediate learners this was not the case. This suggests that native comprehension of ‘harder’ side angles may in part be achieved by mentally rotating signs. We propose the general preference for a front angle could result from high frequency exposure to this angle in both L1 and L2 input.
Novice L2 learners with no signing experience could help determine whether the angle noise effect arises through frequency of exposure to linguistic input, or if body movements are generally difficult to process from side angles. The present study aims to tightly control the frequency of exposure to signs from different angles in order to explore the role of viewing angle in novice lexical sign learning. Furthermore, building on findings that show benefits of diverse input in spoken L2 learning, we are interested in whether teaching signs from multiple angles instead of a single angle could mitigate the ‘noise’ of side angles. Lastly, we want to know whether new learners with better mental rotation skills are better at processing signs when viewed from a previously unseen angle. If diverse angle input and/or visuospatial cognitive aptitude play a role in novice sign learning, this would suggest they should be important considerations in L2 teaching settings, materials and methods.

q4.value:
Experiment 1: learning signs from either a front angle (0° only) or a side angle (90° only); all testing using the same viewing angle seen during learning 
Null hypothesis: non-directional - no difference in recognition accuracy and speed across learning conditions, suggesting side angles are not noisy for novice learners.
Alternative hypothesis: directional - signs learned at 0° will be recognised quicker and more accurately than those learned at 90°, suggesting sign comprehension at side angles is also noisy for novice learners.
Experiment 2: learning signs from either a single front angle (0° only)  or a single offset angle (45° only) or multiple angles (both 0° and 45°); all testing from a previously unseen profile angle (90°).
Null hypothesis: non-directional - no difference between the three angle conditions, suggesting that 90° is equally noisy regardless of learning condition, and frequency of input is the most important factor.
Alternative hypothesis 1: directional - faster and more accurate recognition for signs taught from multiple angles (both 0° and 45°) than those taught from a single angle (0° only; or 45° only), suggesting that diversity of angle in learning input is the most important factor
Alternative hypothesis 2: directional - faster and more accurate recognition for signs learned at 45° only, followed by the both angles condition, and lastly those learned at 0° only, suggesting mental rotation of signs is the most important factor (since 45° is closest to the 90° test angle).
Alternative hypothesis 3: directional - faster and more accurate recognition for signs learned at 0° only, followed by the both angles condition, and lastly those learned at 45° only, suggesting visibility/exposure to the front angle during learning is the most important factor.
 
Individual differences measures: mental rotation and digit span
Null hypothesis: non-directional - there will be no relationship between performance in the sign learning tasks and on the mental rotation task or digit span task.
Alternative hypothesis: directional - learners with better mental rotation skills will perform better at the sign learning tasks. In particular, learners with good mental rotation skills will be faster and more accurate to signs presented from the previously unseen angle in Experiment 2 than learners with poor mental rotation skills. However, we predict no relation between performance on the sign learning tasks and a second individual difference measure (digit span).

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: For studies that involve human subjects, they will not know the treatment group to which they have been assigned.

q7.value: Participants will not know which items are in which learning conditions or that there are even different learning conditions. Participants are also unaware which experiment versions/lists they have been assigned (see Study design). The link between the sign learning tasks and the other two cognitive tasks (digit span & mental rotation) will not be explained until the experiment de-brief.

question.value: Within-participants, between-items design: all participants complete both experiments and are exposed to all items and all angle conditions. The angle condition of items varies across two versions of Experiment 1 and three versions of Experiment 2, which are randomly assigned to the participant. Items are counterbalanced within all blocks for three sign types (one-handed signs, two-handed asymmetrical signs and two-handed symmetrical signs). Block order is counterbalanced across versions during learning and all items are fully randomised during testing. Design of the block rotation task is similar: within participants, between-items: all participants see all shapes and all rotation conditions. The rotation condition of shapes varies across four versions of the experiment, one of which is randomly assigned to the participant. Further details in previous Hypotheses section and

q9.value: Order of tasks is not randomised: 1) Experiment 1 learning phase, 2) short break, 3) Experiment 1 test, 4) short break, 5) Experiment 2 learning phase, 6) short break, 7) Experiment 2 test, 8) Mental Rotation task, 9) Digit Span task. Items are randomised within block in the learning phases, but blocks are ordered to ensure iterations of signs are roughly equally spread. Item order is fully randomised during the final tests, however

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: Undergraduate students from the University of Birmingham will be recruited via the Research Participation Scheme system and will receive 1 credit, or £7 for their time. Participants must be 18 years old, right-handed, with native English as their only proficient language, no sign language experience, and normal/corrected vision.

q14.value: The initial study on angle effects on sign processing in BSL users (Watkins et al., in prep) tested 45 participants total, with four groups of ~11 participants each, tested on 240 known signs. The previous angle learning study test one group of 60 novice learners on 96 signs. In order to learn signs as a novice, they should be presented multiple times, so fewer items with more iterations are required. This time, we have two experiments: the first has n=30 items and the second n=54 items (84 total). This is slightly reduced from 96 due to the increases in difficulty. Any more than this would be overwhelming for complete beginners in a single experiment and unnecessarily increase the length of the experiment, also with respect to the time constraints of participation via the Research Participation Scheme. Therefore, we will test a larger sample of 72 novice learners as a compromise for the smaller number of items and greater iterations required.

question.value:
Viewing angle of signs during learning and testing.
Experiment 1: Learning in two single-angle conditions: 0° only (n=15); 90° only (n=15). Testing angle is the same as the angle learned at.
Experiment 2: Learning in three single or multiple angle conditions: 0° only (n=18); 45° only (n=18); both 0° and 45° (n=18). All testing is at a new, previously unseen angle (90°).
Mental rotation task: degree of rotation of required: 0° (n=24); 50° (n=24); 100° (n=24); 150° (n=24).
Digit span task: length of digit span: 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10 (n=3 at each length)

Naming speed reaction time (ms) (voice onset measured from the onset of the sign video)
Naming accuracy
For the block rotation task and digit span tasks, button press reaction time and accuracy will be measured.

Experiment 1 & 2, linear mixed models:
ErrorRate ~ Condition + (1 + Condition|Subject) + (1 + Condition|Sign)
RT ~ Condition + (1 + Condition|Subject) + (1 + Condition|Sign)
ErrorRate ~ Condition + Iconicity + (1 + Condition|Subject) + (1 + Condition|Sign)
RT ~ Condition + Iconicity + (1 + Condition|Subject) + (1 + Condition|Sign)
ErrorRate ~ Condition + SignType + (1 + Condition|Subject) + (1 + Condition|Sign)
RT ~ Condition + SignType + (1 + Condition|Subject) + (1 + Condition|Sign)
If models fail to converge, the random effects structure will be reduced.

Simple correlation (Pearson’s r) between mental rotation accuracy and BSL learning accuracy (over participant means)
Simple correlation (Pearson’s r) correlational between mental rotation RT and BSL learning RT (over participant means)
Simple correlation (Pearson’s r) between digit span and BSL learning accuracy (over participant means)

q20.value: Reaction time will be log transformed.

q21.value: We will use the standard p<.05 criteria for determining whether the linear mixed models suggest that the results are significantly different from those expected if the null hypothesis were correct.

q22.value: No outliers will not be excluded. Response window is pre-determined as 0-4000ms so extremely slow RTs are already excluded through the experiment design.

q23.value: Data partially missing due to a participant quitting the experiment will be excluded. Data partially missing due to unforeseen software errors will be retained for analysis. Reaction times that are missing due to the voice key failing to trigger will be recovered using Chronset (Roux, Armstrong & Carreiras, 2016).

q24.value: Data from 4 pilot participants has been examined to ensure that the difficulty of Experiment 2 is increased from the previous learning study design. Mean accuracy from the new pilot participants is 65.2% in Experiment 1 and 62.5% in Experiment 2, compared to 86% in the previous design.

attributes.title: Using Intellectual Humility to Navigate Existential Challenges

q1.value: Lab Study of Intellectual Humility for Navigating Existential Issues and Political Discussions

q3.value:
Humility involves (a) an accurate or moderate view of one’s strengths and weaknesses as well as being (b) interpersonally other-oriented rather than self-focused, marked by the ability to restrain egotism (i.e., self-oriented emotions such as pride or shame) in ways that maintain social acceptance (Davis et al, 2011). Whereas humility refers to a variety of domains, intellectual humility (IH) pertains to one’s knowledge or intellectual influence. Namely, IH involves having (a) insight about the limits of one’s knowledge, marked by openness to new ideas; and (b) regulating arrogance, marked by the ability to present one’s ideas in a nonoffensive manner and receive contrary ideas without taking offense, even when confronted with alternative viewpoints. (Mcelroy et al., 2014).
The reason this is being conducted is to study how intellectually humble people react to those who disagree with them. Specifically, we are interested in whether intellectual humility can buffer against defensive responding in situations that typically elicit strong attitudes (i.e., existential reminders). In particular, people will be randomly assigned to consider an existential concern (e.g., mortality) or a neutral topic (e.g., dental pain) and then engage in a discussion with an ideologically dissimilar other. We predict that people high in intellectual humility will be less defensive and more open to dissimilar others.

In this laboratory study, we are examining the interactive effects of intellectual humility and mortality salience on responses toward an ideologically dissimilar discussion partner. 

Participants will complete demographics information, scales related to their intellectual humility, measures regarding their political beliefs (including opinions about immigration and gun control), and then be randomly assigned to either a mortality salience or a dental pain priming induction. Following this, participants will interact with an ideologically dissimilar other (based on political views) for 5 minutes. (Participants who provide additional consent will have this discussion interaction video recorded for future coding.) After this discussion, they will complete a scales about their interaction with their partner, including rating their discussion partner. 

Following this, participants will be told that they are still working with their partner on a “food preference” study, wherein one person will prepare food that the other must eat. Based a on fixed “random” assignment, participants will select to be the food preparer and must prepare crackers and hot sauce for their partner, whose food preference sheet indicates that she/he does not like spicy food. However, the food taster but eat all of the food prepared by the food preparer. Thus, the last measure is one of behavioral aggression, in the form of the weight of hot sauce administered to the contention discussion partner by the participant.

q4.value:
A Priori Hypotheses:

H1: We predict a main effect for mortality salience, wherein those primed to think about their own death will rate their discussion partner more negatively (H1a) and will administer more hot sauce to their partner (H1b) relative to those primed with dental pain.

H2: We predict a main effect for intellectual humility, wherein those high in intellectual humility will rate their discussion partner more favorably (H2a) and will administer less hot sauce to their partner (H2b) relative to those low in intellectual humility.

H3: We predict an interaction effect, whereby intellectual humility will attenuate the effects of mortality salience on self-reported ratings (H3a) and hot sauce administration (H3b).
